Beispiel Batch Funktion Bedeckungsgrad

library(dplyr)
library(purrr)
source("batch_bedeckungsgrad.R")
file_list <- list.files(path = "../data/", pattern = "jpg")
file_list
[1] "Spinat1.jpg" "Spinat2.jpg" "Spinat3.jpg" "Spinat4.jpg"
[5] "Spinat5.jpg" "Spinat6.jpg" "Spinat7.jpg"

Anwendung fuer ein einzelnes Bild:

a <- batch_bedeckungsgrad(image_in_path = "../data/",
                          image_in_file = "F4a_Tag_25.JPG", 
                          image_out_path = "../figures/Spinat_2020/",
                          image_out_file = "Bedeckungsgrad1.jpeg")

Anwendung fuer ganzen Ordner:

alle_bedeckungsgrade <- 
    map_df(file_list,
           ~batch_bedeckungsgrad(image_in_path = "../data/",
                                 image_in_file = .x, 
                                 image_out_path = "../figures/Spinat_2020/",
                                 image_out_file = .x)
    )
alle_bedeckungsgrade

#Tabelle speichern:

data.table::fwrite(alle_bedeckungsgrade, file = "../data/bedeckungsgrade.csv", sep = ";")
